{
  "family": "Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag Reaction (Remote Functionalization)",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CCCCN(C)Cl"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "C1CCCN1C"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O",
      "[H+]"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic and simple example of the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. N-chloro-N-methylbutylamine undergoes a 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer via a nitrogen-centered radical, generated under acidic and photolytic/thermal conditions. The resulting carbon-centered radical then abstracts a chlorine atom to form a delta-chloroamine, which cyclizes upon treatment with base (implicitly formed or added) to yield N-methylpyrrolidine. This example clearly demonstrates the key remote C-H functionalization and subsequent intramolecular cyclization to form a five-membered ring, which is characteristic of this reaction.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The reaction involves a specific intramolecular C-H functionalization via a nitrogen radical, followed by cyclization. It avoids common motifs like arenes, diazo groups, or complex ring systems. The substrate is a simple acyclic N-haloamine, and the product is a simple pyrrolidine, which is distinct from reactions like the Beckmann rearrangement (oximes to amides), Hofmann rearrangement (amides to amines), or other radical cyclizations that do not start from an N-haloamine under these specific conditions."
  }
}
